In the 1960s, Brando starred in films such as One-Eyed Jacks (1961), a western that was the only film he ever directed; Mutiny on the Bounty (1962), The Chase (1966), and Reflections in a Golden Eye (1967), portraying a repressed gay army officer. It was the type of performance that later led critic Stanley Crouch to write, \Brando's main achievement was to portray the taciturn but stoic gloom of those pulverized by circumstances.\"Crouch